  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "Evolution is stuck at a fixed point in strategy space. Fitness = 0.641 is not low; it means the population has saturated its current niche and all paths to higher fitness are blocked by the current rules. The system needs DEGREES OF FREEDOM it doesn't have: morphological (cell types), behavioral (state/memory), or environmental (non-stationary selection pressure). Without these, evolution is constrained optimization of a fixed function. Add any one, fitness will spike as organisms rediscover higher peaks in the expanded space.; [hard] Introduce specialized cell types with role-specific functions (sensory, contractile, metabolic, reproductive) that can emerge during organism growth and pass through inheritance. Currently organisms likely have uniform cells — morphological constraints limit what evolution can build. — Plateaus happen when the search space is exhausted. Multi-type cell differentiation expands the morphological space from 1D (single cell type, optimize its parameters) to N-dimensional (cell types × roles × integration rules). Organisms can evolve internal complexity, not just external shape. Beauty can now reward intricate internal structure.; [medium] Add organism state/memory: each organism carries internal counters that persist across decision cycles (energy reserves, 'mood' state, mating readiness). Decision function becomes f(sensory_input, internal_state) → action + new_state, not just f(sensory_input) → action. Allow inheritance of initial state biases. — Current decisions are likely reactive/memoryless. This forces organisms to settle at single-strategy equilibrium. With state memory, organisms can implement conditional strategies, predator-avoidance timing, energy-driven behavior, resource-hoarding cycles. Evolution discovers temporal coordination impossible in stateless agents.; [easy] Replace static world physics with cyclic resource scarcity: nutrients cycle through abundance/famine phases (e.g., 50-cycle boom, 50-cycle scarcity). Predator/prey pressure also cycles. Organisms must now evolve strategies that perform well across multiple regimes, not one fixed equilibrium. — Fitness plateau suggests the population has converged to locally-optimal stable strategies in a constant environment. Cyclic pressure breaks monoculture — generalists and specialists both survive depending on phase. Evolution becomes a moving target, forcing continual adaptation rather than settling at a peak.",
